                        <div id="agenda-intro">
                          <h2>Introduction to Agenda</h2>
                          <div class="divide20"></div>
                          <h3>Case 1: Nuclear Weapon Free Zones (NWFZ)</h3>
                          <p>The motto of the IAEA is “ Atoms for Peace,” which supplements it objective of strengthening nuclear security and restricting nuclear arsenals of nations. Since its establishment the IAEA has been instrumental in establishing Nuclear Weapon Free Zones (NWFZ) in the African Continent, Latin America, Central and Southeast Asia under specific treaties. Creation Of NWFZ’s is integral in strengthening the Non Proliferation Treaty ( NPT ) and in decreasing nuclear stockpiles .The committee must address the feasibility of NWFZ’s and the laws governing  safeguards of maintaining such zones under the mandate of the IAEA. The major aspect of the agenda at DSMUN will be the discussion on the possibility of establishing a Nuclear Weapon Free Zone (NWFZ) in the Middle East.</p>
                          <h3>Case 2: North Korea Hydrogen Bomb Test</h3>
                          <p>Recent developments have seen North Korea emerge as nuclear regime with constant armament and increase in its nuclear arsenal. Despite various economic sanctions and embargos imposed upon North Korea by the United Nations Security Council, North Korea carried out its fourth nuclear test since the rise of its military dictator Kim Jon Un. This nuclear test also triggered an earthquake of magnitude 5.1 on the Richter scale according to reports of the South Korean media. The components of the Hydrogen bomb detonated by North Korea are also unknown. The IAEA can no longer wait and watch; it must take measures to restrict the nuclear power of North Korea.
                            </p>

